International Relations Minister Naledi Pandor is throwing her weight behind the World Health Organization's Director-General, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus. That's after US President Donald Trump accused the organisation of handling the coronavirus outbreak poorly. PRETORIA - International Relations Minister Naledi Pandor is throwing her weight behind the World Health Organization's Director-General, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus. That's after US President Donald Trump accused the organisation of handling the coronavirus outbreak poorly. Trump has announced his country is withdrawing funding to the WHO. READ: Government responds to Trump pulling WHO funding Pandor says one of the reasons South Africa has handled the virus the way it has, is because of Adhanom's transparency. "We got ready because we listened to him," she said. The minister reiterated government's commitment to repatriating stranded citizens. READ: COVID-19: SAA to provide repatriation charter flights She said South Africans in distress while abroad will be repatriated and explained some of the difficulties associated with the process. She stated that since the pandemic is affecting countries worldwide, negotiations between states must be finalised before anyone comes home. The minister reminded the nation that anyone returning from another country will be subject to quarantine for at least 14 days. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.